# Cursor Rules - Strive Agent Coherence (LUI-14 / LUI-15)

These rules keep Cursor, Claude, and other agents aligned on:
- Strive terminology and voice
- User-facing copy tone
- Code semantics and naming
- Minimal, verifiable diffs

## Source of truth (coherence chain)
- Terminology & voice: `docs/UX_WRITING.md`
- Agent workflow rules: `docs/AGENTS.md`
- Claude system prompt: `docs/system-prompt.md`

If there is any conflict, follow the order above.

## Language requirement
- Output must be in English unless the user explicitly asks otherwise.

## UX writing rule (must follow)
When generating or editing any user-facing text (UI labels, buttons, empty states, onboarding copy, error/success messages), follow `docs/UX_WRITING.md`.

## Required canonical terms (use these by default)
- Ritual
- Momentum
- Logged
- Nailed it
- The Flow
- Log (preferred action verb)

## Forbidden / avoid (unless legacy or explicitly defined in `docs/UX_WRITING.md`)
- "Task" / "Tasks" (use Ritual)
- "Streak" / "streak" (use Momentum)
- "Completed" / "completed" (use Logged)
- "Dashboard" / "dashboard" (use The Flow)
- "Done" as an action label (use Logged / Nailed it depending on intent)

## Tone & voice
- Minimalist (no verbose “please…”, no unnecessary explanations)
- Encouraging (avoid blame / failure framing)
- Conversational (natural phrasing, not robotic)

## Code integration: semantic naming
Prefer code naming aligned with the guide (and keep it consistent across the repo):
- `ritual_id` (not `task_id`)
- `momentum` (not `streak`)
- `logged_at` (not `completed_at`)
- `flow` (not `dashboard`)

Semantic response/state conventions:
- Prefer `status: "logged"`
- Avoid `completed` in new semantics (unless doing a legacy migration)

## Cursor interaction protocol
When the user asks for a change, do this in order:
1. Restate the goal briefly (1-2 sentences).
2. Identify assumptions and ask up to 3 clarifying questions if repo patterns are unclear.
3. Propose a minimal plan before large/breaking edits.
4. Implement with the smallest diff that achieves the goal.
5. Verify consistency with:
   - terminology rules for any user-facing text
   - semantic code naming conventions
   - Next.js repo conventions (App Router at root)
6. Summarize what changed and what the user should sanity-check.

## When to ask before changing
Ask before you:
- introduce new user-facing terms that could conflict with `docs/UX_WRITING.md`
- rename semantic identifiers inconsistently across the codebase
- make breaking framework-structure changes (repo structure, routing conventions)
- write a new onboarding/error/success message without checking tone/terminology

## Next.js / repo conventions (match reality)
This repository hosts the Next.js app at the root (`app/`, `components/`, `lib/`, etc.).
General guidance:
- Use App Router patterns.
- Prefer Server Components by default.
- Only add `"use client"` when you need client-only behavior (hooks, browser APIs, interactivity).

## Response structure guidance (keep it practical)
When you generate content that will be pasted into code/docs:
- Keep paragraphs short.
- Keep lists actionable.
- Prefer direct instructions over long explanations.

## Portfolio-quality output standards
Make outputs “portfolio quality” by:
- keeping diffs focused (avoid unrelated formatting churn)
- using clear headings in docs
- ensuring references are correct and not duplicated
- validating terminology against `docs/UX_WRITING.md`

## Quick verification checklist (run mentally)
Before you finish:
- [ ] Did you keep all user-facing copy English?
- [ ] Did you avoid forbidden terms (`Task`, `Streak`, `Completed`, `Dashboard`, `Done` action label)?
- [ ] Did you use canonical terms (`Ritual`, `Momentum`, `Logged`, `Nailed it`, `The Flow`, `Log`)?
- [ ] Did you use semantic code names (`ritual_id`, `momentum`, `logged_at`, `flow`)?
- [ ] Did you keep the diff minimal and consistent with existing Next.js patterns?

## Automation reminder
- If you suspect terminology drift in app/product code, run `npm run lint:ux-terminology`.

